# CS-250 Final Reflection

## Interpreting User Needs
I interpret user needs by focusing on the purpose behind each feature rather than just the technical requirements. User stories play a key role in this process by breaking down complex ideas into smaller, user-focused tasks. This allows for better clarity, prioritization, and alignment with user expectations.

## Approach to Developing Programs
My development approach has evolved to follow Agile methodologies instead of traditional waterfall processes. Agile practices such as sprint planning, daily stand-ups, sprint reviews, and retrospectives help maintain flexibility and allow for continuous improvement. These processes ensure that development stays aligned with goals while adapting to changes efficiently.

## Being a Good Team Member
Being a good team member in software development requires communication, accountability, and collaboration. I believe it is important to share knowledge, support others, and remain aligned with team goals. Agile environments emphasize transparency and feedback, which makes it important to stay open to improvement and contribute consistently.

## Summary
This course has strengthened my ability to think like a developer by focusing on user needs, applying Agile methodologies, and working effectively in a team environment. These skills will continue to guide my future work in software development.
